The Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to combat electoral fraud.
The Brennan Centre considers the latter a myth, claiming that electoral fraud is less rare in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In addition, Republican lawyers reported only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will undermine the American democratic system in part.
Unlike in Canada, U.S. states are responsible for the organization of federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of U.S. governments enacted new laws that made the registration or voting process more difficult from 2009 onwards.
This phenomenon took on a large scale after the November 2010 elections, which included 675 new republican representatives in 26 States.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of voting rights in 41 States were introduced in the only year 2011.
New electoral laws require voters to present an identity card with a photo and proof of American citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce periods of advance voting, invalidate the right to register as an elector on polling day, and remove citizens with legal records from their right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present an identity card with a photo.
Indiana was the first State to make such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of Indiana's law.
The republican authorities were trying to extend this practice to other States.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID card.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have identity cards issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity.
However, it often costs more than $100 to obtain the required ID card.
New restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens aged over 65 and 20% of voters aged 18-29 do not have the required identity card with a photo.
A lot more.
Students, voters considered to be more voting for democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their identity card with a photo issued by their institutions.
On the other hand, these same States allow the members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use to vote on the cards issued by these clubs.
Before 2004, no State required evidence of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to present such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures clearly aim to limit Hispanic voting.
But he learns that two out of three Hispanic voters favor the Democratic party.
In addition, the Republican legislators sponsored in 2011 laws abolishing voter registration on polling day in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequence.
For example, during the 2004 general election, electoral registration campaigns contributed to the registration of approximately 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 dropped the registration rate of new voters by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have adopted legislation in five other States to reduce the voting period in advance.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of the electors who voted in advance were African-American, while the electors represented only 13% of the state's electors.
He was also going with the Hispanics.
They represented only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, the whites that formed 76% of the electors represented only 46% of the electors voting in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
