Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of this agency, the second Member State of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and over the years that followed participated in a number of Agency projects.
The road from Poland to space, however, began much earlier.
Already before World War II, passionate Poles worked on space flights; they did not always find understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, A. Šternfeld's conference at the Warsaw astronomical observatory on 6 December 1933, in which he presented ideas from his avant-garde work entitled Introduction to Astronautics.
The developments of this young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold and years later Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie Prize in France and André Louis Hirsch for his book - Introduction to Astronautics.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronomy.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski has become a world-renowned astronomical propagator, and his contribution has been rewarded in particular by the fact that his name has been given to one of the craters on the hidden face of the Moon.
By 1925 a drain was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
Nor is it clear whether the rocket should be used to propel or brake the drain.
The only information known about this drachma is that of the press of the time.
Starting in 1933, the Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustav Mokrzyckiego.
It appears from the preserved documents that this research had reached the stage of the tests.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the research stopped.
In 1937, plans for a photo-electric hunting rocket, designed by the engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year the book \"Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietbomba lotnicza\" was published by a author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were aimed at military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all rocket technology projects were conducted by the interim scientific advisory committee \"Tymczasowy Committeeet Doradczo-Naukowy\", which coordinated all work.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other works devoted to the aircraft were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish astronomical society (Polskie Towarzystwo Atronautyczne).
For the first time, it is about a company in the November 1954 issue of the Journal Problem, in which there are four more detailed articles devoted to aircraft.
In one of these articles, written by Professor Mr Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronomy.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronomical Society (PTA) made efforts to enter the International Astronomical Federation (created in 1951) and in the fall, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the international astronomical federation.
He retained his function until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the Meteorological rocket MRI (Rakieta Meteorologicalzna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters was 80 cm long and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version, RM-1A, was built and during the summer of 1959, two-storey RM-2 rocket flight tests were started in the Bledov desert.
This rocket was 1.4 meters long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The following prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have ranged up to 14.5 km and served to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, followed by the first RM rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they distinguished themselves by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space with a volume of 0.4 litres, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 litre and in Meteor-1C 0.62 litres.
The maximum range of all these types of equipment was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the Aeronautical Institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a useful load of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were subsequently built.
The entry of Poland to COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later, should be mentioned.
As part of the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimir Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of the programme.
