The film Argo: When everything goes to the worst, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of protestors made up of Islamist students attacked the American Embassy of Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had supported his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the US administration a positive outcome, it could not, in fact, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously undermined the trust of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the liberation of hostages.
It was a tough blow to the prestige of the United States, which was further aggravated by the fiasco of the attempt to release hostages by force.
The kidnapped diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following the negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate in the United States provokes a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranism.
The Iranian debacle greatly contributed to Jimmy Carter's defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered a small victory in America.
Just before she was occupied, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated periods, they found themselves in the Ambassador of Canada's residence.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran thanks to a rock cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a shooting team who came to make screenings for shooting a film with a great science-fiction performance.
Combination of genres
Exfiltration expert Tony Mendez's plan requires Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized shops reported on this film project, press conferences were held and a fictitious production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
This is part of a political thriller designed in a realistic way, but also a \"moving cap\" - the story of a successful coup, a betrayal - like, for example, in the ocean's trilogy raise, tweet and thirteen.
Ambiences happen: sequences of Tehran in documentary style (in the captioned sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and the way in which, thanks to these photos, these same situations were retranslated in the film, there are no major differences),
the lightest passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
and then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions with custom men discussing the situation around conference tables, corridors and telephones...
Ben Affleck was able to reboot his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and his acting game ceased to raise ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark police - Gone Baby Gone - (2007) and the thriller - Thetown - (2010).
It's also Affleck's first film that doesn't take place in his home town, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above the Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of the atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran is held by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place on the streets, during the reconstruction of actual facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive by its clarity which also suggests the confusion and unpredictability occurring when suddenly, in a given place, a history page is written.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect on fictional scenes (the fake shooting team in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions to too many places
The director had to be content with a subject that offered in fact only a few striking scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
He's doing very well, he sometimes adds some elements to the reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the crisis threat at Tehran airport is removed by a phone shot in America and the pursuit on the runway are quite fired by the hair).
Argo's weakness lies in his dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events at too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood co-ops, their characters would have deserved a bigger place and they are not, far from it, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks some dramatic tension, it shows itself with moderate interest, appreciating the realization and retro style of the 1970s.
It drives the viewer, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story yet, in a certain way, unfinished to date, and as an illustration of the exaggerated nature of the representation of secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the matter.
