Szabo: -Germans must play a greater role -
Germany chose abstention during the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert in relations between the United States and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian demand for observer status with the United Nations.
But then she chose abstention.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, however, without being overly critical of Israel.
At the insurrection in Libya in March 2011, Germany had also chosen to abstain in the vote on the establishment of an area of air exclusion.
Finally, NATO imposes this measure.
Does Germany find it difficult to adopt a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
In addition, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans are fighting on several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they still cheat to find this role, but they're on the road to a more normal foreign policy.
External policy, such as in France or Great Britain
What does the term \"normal\" foreign policy mean to the Germans in practice?
It shows the desire to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national dossiers.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, so by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to some extent, different from those of other great powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position vis-à-vis the conflict in the Middle East and its abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany first had important opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must take care not to strike public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive element.
However, I would not attach too much importance to it, because it is not a purely unilateral relationship.
But this is, in any case, a key element in German strategic reflections.
Does Germany neglect its relationship with the United States by choosing abstention in major votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I think that the fracture is not so serious that it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Maybe even Germany will only be more respected.
Indeed, Germany has shown that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do the views differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American internal political scene.
I believe that the Obama Administration secretly demonstrates a great understanding of the European position.
But given the country's political configuration, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not so great that they always seem so.
If you observe the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahou, you will notice that Obama is far from enthusiastic about Netanyahou's policy.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I don't think it makes things easier for the Germans.
Obviously, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today that is not the case.
They cannot, therefore, register within a broader political line and must affirm their individual position.
This is what they are currently doing in the euro issue.
In my view, Germany will in future take a role as a locomotive and will move Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not easy for Germany, especially because of its relationship with Israel.
This question has always been delicate.
But I believe the Germans are well aware that they must play a role that is more important to their independence.
Does Germany see itself playing a leading role on the international stage, but does Germany just want to play a key role?
Or does it still have difficulty taking on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country still finds it difficult to play a more important role.
If one looks at, for example, the euro crisis, it is observed that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make things easier for the Germans.
In fact, it is still the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It must be composed of very diverse neighbours and opinions, and it is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy only diminishes, but right now the EU does not fill this vacuum, but who remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and if they're only less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy of Washington, an institute in which academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyze the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
