Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, the prosecutors declare.
Prosecutors are trying to counter the claims of abuse that Bradley Manning was allegedly the victim of incarceration.
The trial involves Manning's detention in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence wants to rank the case on the grounds that Manning's kidnapping was made in extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
The prosecutors tried to prove, Friday, that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of being the source of the biggest leak of confidential information from the entire history of the U.S. Army -- had missed many opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he claimed to have suffered during his military detention.
During a cross-examination with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Maj. Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits to Manning by officers during his nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints about his treatment.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defence filed a request demanding that the Manning case be classified on the ground that the kidnapping took place under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place one day after Manning testified to his desire to commit suicide during his detention.
This military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were then posted online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed that Manning had been their source.
At the Friday hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that the officers had completed after their meeting with Manning during his detention in the military prison in Quantico, where he was subjected to maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein mentioned the forms, Friday, Manning recognized that the treatment he had reserved for his guards was \"excellent\" and that the treatment he had had in prison was generally \"very professional\"
The forms did not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although the officers questioned him directly about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had orally expressed concerns about certain problems and that the visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would deal with them, but they did not record the issues raised.
\"They wrote -- no problems -- (after addressing the concerns), and yet that didn't mean I didn't raise any problems,\" Manning said.
Military judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment during a meeting in January 2011 with the special commission that met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during the meeting was to amend his restrictive status indicating a \"risk of injury\"
The military stated that they had assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for the risk of suicide -- for his protection and safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know that I was going well, and I wanted this status to be removed... in order to enjoy a better quality of life from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for almost two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Marine Corps Base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He stated that he considered suicide when he was in Kuwait and escaped once because of the heat.
He added that the fact that he was not kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was happening in the rest of the world was very distressing.
\"My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, in this cage,\" said Manning, Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in this cage.
Once in Quantico, Manning stated that he had spent the most light of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only objects he had were mattresses, blankets, tongs, clothes and glasses.
He tried to stay on the move, as sleeping or staying lying down during the day was contrary to the rules.
Manning also specified that when he was trying to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards didn't see his face when he came back at night, they would wake him up so that he could see his face.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning's treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
On Friday, too, the judge asked Manning about an allegation in his testimony of Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked all night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of the guards and other prisoners one morning during the call.
Manning testified that at no time, he was allowed to cover himself with a cover during the appeal.
During the judge's questions on Friday, Manning stated that he had deducted from his guard's order that he should have dropped his cover which could have hidden his nudity, but he recognized that no one had ordered him to let it go.
Manning testified on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before, as he would have tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning would have told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his slip or tongs to hurt himself, but that he did not.
That night Manning testified that his underwear, his tongs, and his glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account the experiences he has experienced during his detention and that he will significantly reduce his sentence if he is to be convicted before a court martial, a trial that should be held early next year.
The defence stated that Manning plans to plead guilty to the less serious crimes and to fight for the abandonment of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing should resume this weekend, with prosecutors who should argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon confirmed that Manning was incarcerated in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention of all detainees in Quantico.
The charges brought against Manning include theft of public goods or documents, collusion with the enemy, giving rise to the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of information on national defence.
If all the charges are dismissed, he will be sentenced to life imprisonment.
