For four euros, Indonesian volcano carriers risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 minors who earn their lives by carrying the sulphur of the Kawah Ijen volcano, to the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
He must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where sulphur gas from the earth's entrances solidifies in contact with the air.
After harvesting large sulphur rocks, which weigh about 70 kilos in total, it installs them in two bamboo baskets that it loads on its shoulders across the steep trails.
There are only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which peaks at 2,386 meters high, but the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to grave this distance, with a tortuous look, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost them their lives, as it happened to a French tourist who had a fatal fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Kawah Ijen minors earn 5 cents of euro for each kilo of sulphur extracted.
